1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,860
Welcome back to the Deep Dive. I want to start today by asking you to do something a little weird.

2
00:00:06,100 --> 00:00:09,780
Wherever you are, unless you're driving, please keep your hands on the wheel if you're driving.

3
00:00:10,200 --> 00:00:14,100
But if you can, I want you to look at your hand. Just hold it up in front of your face,

4
00:00:14,280 --> 00:00:16,600
wiggle your fingers, look at the thumb, really look at it.

5
00:00:16,660 --> 00:00:21,180
Okay, I'm looking at mine. It's a hand. Five fingers, palm, lines.

6
00:00:21,320 --> 00:00:24,220
It's a marvel of engineering, right? The dexterity, the grip strength.

7
00:00:24,560 --> 00:00:28,380
But it's also a biological machine with very real linets.

8
00:00:28,380 --> 00:00:33,040
It has muscles that get tired. It has nerves that have a maximum transmission speed.

9
00:00:33,160 --> 00:00:36,800
It has a specific range of motion. It cramps up if you use it too much in one position.

10
00:00:37,060 --> 00:00:43,080
And today, we're going to talk about how that biological machine, that fleshy, cramping, energy-burning tool,

11
00:00:43,340 --> 00:00:45,940
actually shaped the way we think and the way we communicate.

12
00:00:46,260 --> 00:00:51,580
We're talking about writing, but not in the way you usually hear about it in history class or literature class.

13
00:00:51,620 --> 00:00:57,860
We aren't talking about the content of the books. We are talking about the physical act of putting ink on paper.

14
00:00:57,860 --> 00:01:03,160
Right. Usually when we talk about the alphabet, it's this very abstract intellectual history.

15
00:01:03,580 --> 00:01:08,660
Like, the Phoenicians invented the letter A, and then the Greeks rotated it, and the Romans standardized it.

16
00:01:08,780 --> 00:01:14,380
It feels very clean, very academic. It feels like a decision made by minds floating in a void.

17
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:19,420
As if it were designed by a committee of graphic designers sitting in a pristine white room

18
00:01:19,420 --> 00:01:23,720
with unlimited time and resources trying to make the most logical system possible.

19
00:01:23,720 --> 00:01:27,820
Exactly. But the source material we have today argues the complete opposite.

20
00:01:28,700 --> 00:01:33,240
It argues that logic had very little to do with it, and biology had everything to do with it.

21
00:01:34,140 --> 00:01:40,200
We are diving into a fascinating paper titled Embodied Constraint and Minimal Assembly by Flyxion,

22
00:01:40,600 --> 00:01:43,320
published just this year, February 14, 2026.

23
00:01:43,560 --> 00:01:47,620
And the core argument here is that writing is messy. It is a physical struggle.

24
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:52,580
It's a struggle between your hand, which is fundamentally lazy, and your eye, which is fundamentally picky.

25
00:01:52,580 --> 00:01:55,160
I love that framing. Laziness versus pickiness.

26
00:01:56,260 --> 00:02:03,540
And the battlefield where this war took place, the case study for this deep dive, is the Arabic script.

27
00:02:04,540 --> 00:02:06,580
Now, I want to be clear to everyone listening.

28
00:02:07,440 --> 00:02:12,780
Even if you do not speak a word of Arabic, even if you've never tried to read it, you need to stick around.

29
00:02:13,180 --> 00:02:15,020
Because this isn't really a linguistics lesson.

30
00:02:15,300 --> 00:02:19,640
It's a story about human physiology, thermodynamics, and information theory colliding.

31
00:02:19,900 --> 00:02:21,600
It's about how we optimize energy.

32
00:02:21,600 --> 00:02:24,720
The paper uses this term embodied constraint.

33
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:28,360
It sounds heavy, almost philosophical, but it's actually quite intuitive.

34
00:02:28,800 --> 00:02:30,460
Embodied just means in the body.

35
00:02:30,720 --> 00:02:33,840
Writing isn't magic. It's a motor act. It happens in the meat of your hand.

36
00:02:34,300 --> 00:02:35,820
And constraint means limits.

37
00:02:36,220 --> 00:02:38,940
You can only move your pen so fast before you lose control.

38
00:02:39,160 --> 00:02:41,440
You can only write so small before your muscles cramp.

39
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:45,060
You can only remember so many complex shapes before your brain gets overloaded.

40
00:02:45,280 --> 00:02:49,040
And the paper pairs that with the second concept in the title, minimal assembly,

41
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:51,160
which immediately made me think of furniture.

42
00:02:51,160 --> 00:02:54,060
It is the IKEA principle of language, in a way.

43
00:02:54,220 --> 00:02:57,820
Explain that. How is an ancient alphabet like a flat-packed bookshelf?

44
00:02:58,180 --> 00:02:59,720
Well, think about IKEA furniture.

45
00:03:00,360 --> 00:03:05,180
They don't give you a custom-carved Baroque chair that was sculpted from a single giant log.

46
00:03:05,440 --> 00:03:07,360
That would be expensive and hard to transport.

47
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:10,580
Instead, they give you a few standardized parts.

48
00:03:11,020 --> 00:03:13,260
A screw, a dowel, a plank, a bracket.

49
00:03:13,660 --> 00:03:17,180
And by combining those few cheap standardized parts in different ways,

50
00:03:17,300 --> 00:03:20,380
you can build a bed, a desk, a chair, or a shelf.

51
00:03:20,960 --> 00:03:23,620
The paper argues that writing systems evolve the same way.

52
00:03:23,980 --> 00:03:28,040
You don't have a unique, complex painting for every single word in the language.

53
00:03:28,040 --> 00:03:29,580
That would be impossible to learn.

54
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:31,240
Instead, you have a kit of parts.

55
00:03:31,620 --> 00:03:33,780
A curve, a line, a dot, a loop.

56
00:03:33,920 --> 00:03:34,500
That's it.

57
00:03:34,900 --> 00:03:38,840
And you have to assemble those cheap parts to capture the entire universe of human thought.

58
00:03:39,440 --> 00:03:41,100
And the driving force behind this assembly,

59
00:03:41,540 --> 00:03:44,240
and this is the part that really blew my mind, is thermodynamics.

60
00:03:44,840 --> 00:03:46,680
The author actually brings physics into this.

61
00:03:46,820 --> 00:03:47,120
Yes.

62
00:03:47,660 --> 00:03:49,580
This is where Flyxion gets really interesting.

63
00:03:49,720 --> 00:03:52,240
He calls writing a dissipative act.

64
00:03:52,240 --> 00:03:54,480
Which is a fancy way of saying it burns calories.

65
00:03:55,040 --> 00:03:55,960
It burns calories.

66
00:03:56,300 --> 00:03:56,620
Literally.

67
00:03:56,620 --> 00:04:01,300
Every stroke of the pen requires adenosine triphosphate ATP.

68
00:04:01,900 --> 00:04:03,320
It requires metabolic energy.

69
00:04:03,700 --> 00:04:06,720
Your heart has to pump blood to the muscles in your forearm.

70
00:04:06,840 --> 00:04:08,100
Your neurons have to fire.

71
00:04:08,760 --> 00:04:13,340
And the human body is wired through millions of years of evolution to conserve energy.

72
00:04:13,880 --> 00:04:15,680
We are biological misers.

73
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:18,400
We hate spending calories if we don't have to.

74
00:04:18,520 --> 00:04:21,620
Because for most of human history, calories were scarce.

75
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:24,600
So if you can do something with less effort, you will.

76
00:04:24,720 --> 00:04:25,200
Exactly.

77
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:29,720
So if you leave a writer alone for a thousand years, their handwriting will naturally degrade.

78
00:04:29,940 --> 00:04:32,420
It will get simpler, faster, and messier.

79
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:34,020
Curves will straighten out.

80
00:04:34,260 --> 00:04:35,940
Distinct shapes will merge together.

81
00:04:36,300 --> 00:04:37,580
That's the thermodynamic pressure.

82
00:04:37,700 --> 00:04:38,380
That's the entropy.

83
00:04:38,620 --> 00:04:39,620
That's the laziness.

84
00:04:39,760 --> 00:04:40,440
But here's the catch.

85
00:04:40,920 --> 00:04:44,540
If you let that laziness win completely, if you go for 100% efficiency,

86
00:04:45,140 --> 00:04:46,740
your writing just becomes a straight line.

87
00:04:46,940 --> 00:04:47,640
It becomes a hump.

88
00:04:47,680 --> 00:04:50,180
And a straight line contains zero information.

89
00:04:50,320 --> 00:04:50,620
Zero.

90
00:04:50,620 --> 00:04:54,960
If I hand you a paper with a single horizontal line on it, you have no idea if I'm saying,

91
00:04:55,100 --> 00:04:57,140
hello, I love you, or war is declared.

92
00:04:57,360 --> 00:04:58,580
It's completely ambiguous.

93
00:04:58,580 --> 00:05:04,220
So you have this opposing force, the eye, the reader, or really the decoder.

94
00:05:04,220 --> 00:05:06,200
The reader demands distinctness.

95
00:05:07,080 --> 00:05:09,860
The reader needs the shapes to be different enough to tell them apart.

96
00:05:10,380 --> 00:05:16,100
So the script we see today, specifically the Arabic script, is describing the paper as a

97
00:05:16,100 --> 00:05:17,540
stabilized equilibrium.

98
00:05:17,780 --> 00:05:18,540
It's a truce line.

99
00:05:18,640 --> 00:05:24,000
It's the exact point where the hand does the minimum amount of work possible without the eye losing the

100
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:24,900
ability to read it.

101
00:05:25,140 --> 00:05:26,520
It's an economic negotiation.

102
00:05:27,080 --> 00:05:30,300
I will spend this many calories to make this curve, but not a single calorie more.

103
00:05:30,840 --> 00:05:32,740
If I spend less, you can't read it.

104
00:05:32,840 --> 00:05:34,520
If I spend more, I'm wasting energy.

105
00:05:34,740 --> 00:05:40,640
So the alphabet basically evolved to save calories while keeping us from misreading a text.

106
00:05:40,740 --> 00:05:42,360
That is essentially the thesis, yes.

107
00:05:42,420 --> 00:05:45,740
And what's amazing is looking at how that negotiation played out over history.

108
00:05:45,880 --> 00:05:47,880
Because it wasn't a straight line of progress.

109
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:50,380
It was a messy, tiered process.

110
00:05:50,380 --> 00:05:54,440
It involved mistakes, patches, and updates, just like software.

111
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:55,720
Let's get into that history.

112
00:05:56,160 --> 00:05:57,620
The source breaks this down into segments.

113
00:05:57,940 --> 00:06:00,520
The first one is about the skeleton of the script, the rasm.

114
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:01,480
The rasm.

115
00:06:01,760 --> 00:06:03,560
This is the primitive layer of the script.

116
00:06:04,120 --> 00:06:09,060
If you go back to the 7th century, to the very earliest manuscripts of the Quran, or the

117
00:06:09,060 --> 00:06:12,320
early administrative papyri, what you see is stunning.

118
00:06:12,500 --> 00:06:13,620
It's visually beautiful.

119
00:06:13,840 --> 00:06:17,420
It's these sweeping, long, curvy lines.

120
00:06:17,660 --> 00:06:19,560
It looks like waves on an ocean.

121
00:06:19,560 --> 00:06:21,020
But there's a massive problem with it.

122
00:06:21,220 --> 00:06:22,000
A massive problem.

123
00:06:22,320 --> 00:06:24,940
It's almost unreadable by modern standards.

124
00:06:25,060 --> 00:06:27,920
In fact, even experts struggle with it sometimes without context.

125
00:06:28,280 --> 00:06:28,320
Why?

126
00:06:28,480 --> 00:06:30,540
If it's the same language, why is it unreadable?

127
00:06:30,680 --> 00:06:32,960
Because of that motor efficiency we just talked about.

128
00:06:33,320 --> 00:06:34,660
The collabs were writing fast.

129
00:06:34,760 --> 00:06:35,400
They were flowing.

130
00:06:35,700 --> 00:06:39,540
And because they were flowing, they allowed the shapes of different letters to collapse

131
00:06:39,540 --> 00:06:40,240
into each other.

132
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:44,000
They optimized the distinctness right out of the letters.

133
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:47,420
The source mentioned specifically the letters for B, T, and TH.

134
00:06:48,020 --> 00:06:50,680
In Arabic, that's Ba, Ta, and Tai.

135
00:06:51,020 --> 00:06:51,300
Right.

136
00:06:51,700 --> 00:06:53,340
So let's think about the sounds first.

137
00:06:54,180 --> 00:06:56,300
B is a voiced sound using the lips.

138
00:06:56,660 --> 00:06:58,480
T is a sharp stop behind the teeth.

139
00:06:58,820 --> 00:06:59,760
The is a fricative.

140
00:07:00,520 --> 00:07:02,180
They sound totally different.

141
00:07:02,280 --> 00:07:05,480
If I say bat, tat, and that, those are clearly different words.

142
00:07:05,960 --> 00:07:10,500
But in the rasm, the skeletal script, the symbols for these sounds are identical.

143
00:07:10,500 --> 00:07:13,240
They're just a little tooth, a little bump on the line.

144
00:07:13,460 --> 00:07:13,540
Wait.

145
00:07:13,620 --> 00:07:18,160
So if I'm reading a text from the year 650 and I see a bump, just a little ripple in

146
00:07:18,160 --> 00:07:20,360
the line, it could be a B, a T, or a TH.

147
00:07:20,780 --> 00:07:21,120
Yes.

148
00:07:21,520 --> 00:07:22,380
And it gets worse.

149
00:07:22,820 --> 00:07:28,220
That same bump shape is also used for N, none, and Y, yeah, in the beginning or middle

150
00:07:28,220 --> 00:07:28,660
of a word.

151
00:07:28,840 --> 00:07:33,360
So you have five different letters sharing the exact same chassis, the exact same skeleton.

152
00:07:33,560 --> 00:07:34,320
That sounds like a nightmare.

153
00:07:35,020 --> 00:07:39,360
Imagine reading English where B, B, Q, and G were all just written as a circle, and you

154
00:07:39,360 --> 00:07:44,560
had to figure out if the word was bad, dad, pad, or gag, just by guessing.

155
00:07:44,840 --> 00:07:45,940
That is a perfect analogy.

156
00:07:46,060 --> 00:07:47,540
You're relying entirely on context.

157
00:07:47,680 --> 00:07:50,800
The man sat on the, well, it's probably pad or bed, not dad.

158
00:07:50,860 --> 00:07:51,000
Yeah.

159
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:52,940
You act as a detective.

160
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:54,240
You aren't just reading.

161
00:07:54,380 --> 00:07:55,280
You are deciphering.

162
00:07:55,520 --> 00:07:57,760
But that requires a lot of cognitive energy.

163
00:07:57,960 --> 00:08:01,300
We were talking about saving physical energy, but now we're burning brain power.

164
00:08:01,720 --> 00:08:02,900
Huge cognitive load.

165
00:08:02,900 --> 00:08:07,900
And it works fine if you already know the text by heart, which, to be fair, many early

166
00:08:07,900 --> 00:08:09,820
readers of the Quran did.

167
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:11,720
It was an oral tradition first.

168
00:08:11,960 --> 00:08:14,760
The writing was just a mnemonic device, a memory aid.

169
00:08:14,940 --> 00:08:19,280
Ah, so the text was just a reminder of what you already knew, like sheet music for a song

170
00:08:19,280 --> 00:08:19,940
you've already memorized.

171
00:08:20,260 --> 00:08:20,420
Yeah.

172
00:08:20,440 --> 00:08:22,000
You just need to see the shape of the melody.

173
00:08:22,300 --> 00:08:22,700
Exactly.

174
00:08:23,160 --> 00:08:24,300
But then history happens.

175
00:08:24,440 --> 00:08:25,300
The empire grows.

176
00:08:25,560 --> 00:08:30,980
You have non-native speakers in Persia, in Egypt, in Spain, converting to Islam and trying

177
00:08:30,980 --> 00:08:31,620
to learn Arabic.

178
00:08:32,280 --> 00:08:33,620
They don't have the text memorized.

179
00:08:34,100 --> 00:08:37,240
They don't have that native intuition to guess the context.

180
00:08:37,560 --> 00:08:39,760
They look at these bumps and they are lost.

181
00:08:40,140 --> 00:08:41,760
The ambiguity becomes too expensive.

182
00:08:42,240 --> 00:08:43,540
The system is failing.

183
00:08:43,920 --> 00:08:45,520
So the pressure for clarity spikes.

184
00:08:46,260 --> 00:08:47,540
The laziness has gone too far.

185
00:08:47,740 --> 00:08:48,960
The equilibrium is broken.

186
00:08:49,420 --> 00:08:50,200
How do they fix it?

187
00:08:50,480 --> 00:08:54,380
This is where the concept of minimal assembly really shines.

188
00:08:55,300 --> 00:08:59,040
If this were a modern software project, you might say, okay, this code is broken.

189
00:08:59,040 --> 00:09:01,220
Let's delete it and rewrite the whole thing.

190
00:09:01,380 --> 00:09:05,620
Let's invent 28 totally new shapes so B looks nothing like T.

191
00:09:05,820 --> 00:09:06,940
But they didn't do that.

192
00:09:07,020 --> 00:09:07,980
That would be a hard fork.

193
00:09:08,220 --> 00:09:10,120
No, that's too expensive.

194
00:09:10,420 --> 00:09:13,800
That requires retraining an entire civilization.

195
00:09:14,160 --> 00:09:16,900
It requires throwing away all the books you've already written.

196
00:09:17,020 --> 00:09:18,340
Instead, they patched it.

197
00:09:18,400 --> 00:09:20,040
They introduced incremental augmentation.

198
00:09:20,860 --> 00:09:21,220
The dot.

199
00:09:21,360 --> 00:09:21,740
The dot.

200
00:09:21,940 --> 00:09:22,740
The humble dot.

201
00:09:23,100 --> 00:09:27,520
It is perhaps the most important technological invention in the history of the Arabic script.

202
00:09:27,520 --> 00:09:30,720
I really loved the economics of the dot section in the paper.

203
00:09:31,120 --> 00:09:33,740
It treats the dot like a piece of high-tech engineering.

204
00:09:33,980 --> 00:09:34,920
It is a piece of technology.

205
00:09:35,080 --> 00:09:36,640
Think about the motor cost of a dot.

206
00:09:36,880 --> 00:09:39,760
It is the smallest possible mark you can make with a pen.

207
00:09:39,860 --> 00:09:40,640
It's just a tap.

208
00:09:40,820 --> 00:09:43,000
Pen down, pen up, zero drag.

209
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:44,680
Minimal ink usage.

210
00:09:45,300 --> 00:09:46,900
It's cheap energy-wise.

211
00:09:47,140 --> 00:09:50,020
You aren't drawing a complex drag and you're just tapping the page.

212
00:09:50,120 --> 00:09:52,360
But the informational return is massive.

213
00:09:52,820 --> 00:09:53,460
Infinite return.

214
00:09:53,460 --> 00:09:58,360
By adding one cheap dot below that ambiguous bump, it becomes a B.

215
00:09:59,120 --> 00:09:59,960
Two dots above.

216
00:10:00,100 --> 00:10:00,560
It's a T.

217
00:10:01,140 --> 00:10:01,900
Three dots.

218
00:10:01,980 --> 00:10:02,440
It's a T.

219
00:10:03,060 --> 00:10:03,780
One dot above.

220
00:10:03,860 --> 00:10:04,280
It's an N.

221
00:10:04,400 --> 00:10:05,180
Two dots below.

222
00:10:05,300 --> 00:10:05,860
It's a Y.

223
00:10:06,680 --> 00:10:11,380
You have resolved the ambiguity of five different letters without breaking the flow of the script.

224
00:10:11,380 --> 00:10:14,980
So you keep the lazy flowing skeleton because it's fast to write.

225
00:10:15,100 --> 00:10:15,760
That's layer one.

226
00:10:15,920 --> 00:10:21,880
And then you come back and add these tiny high-fidelity data packets, the dots to specify the meaning.

227
00:10:22,200 --> 00:10:23,180
That's layer two.

228
00:10:23,500 --> 00:10:24,580
It's a dual-layer system.

229
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:25,600
It's incredibly sophisticated.

230
00:10:25,920 --> 00:10:28,040
It's like a compression algorithm in your computer.

231
00:10:28,300 --> 00:10:36,060
You transmit the low-res version first, the skeleton, and then you sharpen the image with the high-res details, the dots, only where you need them.

232
00:10:36,120 --> 00:10:38,360
It's amazing that this wasn't designed by a committee.

233
00:10:38,480 --> 00:10:39,380
It just happened.

234
00:10:39,380 --> 00:10:42,180
It evolved. It's survival of the fittest features.

235
00:10:42,380 --> 00:10:46,240
Now, this is where the paper takes a turn that I found absolutely fascinating.

236
00:10:47,060 --> 00:10:51,460
We know that they use dots, but the source talks about where the dots go and how many dots.

237
00:10:51,780 --> 00:10:53,060
Because it turns out it's not random.

238
00:10:53,460 --> 00:10:57,540
There's a deep, hidden connection between the dots on the page and the physics of your mouth.

239
00:10:57,840 --> 00:10:58,140
Yes.

240
00:10:58,540 --> 00:11:00,700
This is the phonological markedness argument.

241
00:11:01,220 --> 00:11:03,800
This is where linguistics and graphic design merge.

242
00:11:03,980 --> 00:11:05,020
Break that down for us.

243
00:11:05,400 --> 00:11:05,840
Markedness.

244
00:11:05,940 --> 00:11:06,520
What does that mean?

245
00:11:06,780 --> 00:11:07,920
It's a linguistics term.

246
00:11:07,920 --> 00:11:11,920
In any language, there are sounds that are easy or default.

247
00:11:12,240 --> 00:11:13,540
We call those unmarked.

248
00:11:13,700 --> 00:11:15,980
They are the path of least resistance for the human mouth.

249
00:11:16,380 --> 00:11:18,100
They are the sounds a baby makes first.

250
00:11:18,220 --> 00:11:19,080
Da, da, da, da.

251
00:11:19,240 --> 00:11:19,700
Exactly.

252
00:11:19,980 --> 00:11:21,540
And then there are sounds that are marked.

253
00:11:21,840 --> 00:11:22,920
They require something extra.

254
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:24,040
They require extra effort.

255
00:11:24,480 --> 00:11:30,500
You have to buzz your vocal cords or blow more air or twist your tongue in a weird way or hold the sound longer.

256
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:36,520
So, unmarked is the default setting and marked is the upgrade package that costs extra energy.

257
00:11:36,620 --> 00:11:36,980
Correct.

258
00:11:37,780 --> 00:11:43,860
And the Flyxion paper argues that the Arabic script unconsciously mapped this physical reality onto the paper.

259
00:11:44,500 --> 00:11:47,540
Extra effort in the mouth equals extra ink on the page.

260
00:11:47,540 --> 00:11:50,400
Let's look at the examples because this is where you can really see it.

261
00:11:50,740 --> 00:11:54,500
The paper brings up D versus D-H, dell and dell.

262
00:11:54,660 --> 00:11:54,960
Right.

263
00:11:55,260 --> 00:11:57,120
So, I want everyone listening to try this.

264
00:11:57,340 --> 00:12:00,400
Say the letter D, da, door, day.

265
00:12:00,840 --> 00:12:01,740
Where is your tongue?

266
00:12:01,960 --> 00:12:04,060
It's just tapping the roots of my mouth behind my teeth.

267
00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:04,680
Duh.

268
00:12:04,980 --> 00:12:05,640
It's a stop.

269
00:12:05,860 --> 00:12:06,540
You block the air.

270
00:12:06,640 --> 00:12:07,360
Then you release it.

271
00:12:07,420 --> 00:12:08,720
It's very simple ballistics.

272
00:12:09,160 --> 00:12:11,860
In the script, the letter dell has no dot.

273
00:12:12,200 --> 00:12:13,200
It is just a curve.

274
00:12:13,380 --> 00:12:15,160
It is the unmarked basic shape.

275
00:12:15,280 --> 00:12:15,540
Okay.

276
00:12:15,880 --> 00:12:17,020
Simple sound, simple shape.

277
00:12:17,300 --> 00:12:18,200
Now, say D-H.

278
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:21,620
This is the sound in the words the or this or that.

279
00:12:21,900 --> 00:12:23,080
In Arabic, it's dell.

280
00:12:23,960 --> 00:12:24,400
The.

281
00:12:25,180 --> 00:12:25,620
This.

282
00:12:25,960 --> 00:12:27,060
What is your tongue doing now?

283
00:12:27,160 --> 00:12:28,280
It's sliding forward.

284
00:12:28,420 --> 00:12:31,720
It's actually between my teeth and I'm blowing air through it.

285
00:12:31,740 --> 00:12:33,180
You are creating turbulence.

286
00:12:33,180 --> 00:12:34,920
That is an interdental fricative.

287
00:12:35,180 --> 00:12:39,360
You are engaging the tongue and the breath and the teeth and you have to sustain it.

288
00:12:39,520 --> 00:12:42,280
It is physically more complex than a simple D.

289
00:12:42,740 --> 00:12:43,740
It is marked.

290
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:44,520
And in the script.

291
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:45,660
It gets a dot.

292
00:12:45,920 --> 00:12:48,240
The dell shape plus a dot equals dell.

293
00:12:48,660 --> 00:12:52,780
The extra physical friction of the tongue is represented by the extra mark of the pen.

294
00:12:53,040 --> 00:12:53,760
That is so cool.

295
00:12:53,840 --> 00:12:56,180
It's like the script is a diagram of the effort.

296
00:12:56,500 --> 00:12:58,880
Here is the base move and here is the extra friction.

297
00:12:59,000 --> 00:12:59,380
Exactly.

298
00:12:59,500 --> 00:13:00,160
Give us another one.

299
00:13:00,220 --> 00:13:00,380
Okay.

300
00:13:00,420 --> 00:13:01,540
Let's take R versus Z.

301
00:13:01,540 --> 00:13:02,420
Ra and Zay.

302
00:13:02,580 --> 00:13:05,600
They look exactly the same in the skeleton, but Zay has a dot.

303
00:13:05,600 --> 00:13:09,660
So the R in Arabic is a tap or a trill.

304
00:13:10,320 --> 00:13:10,460
Ra.

305
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:11,620
It's quick.

306
00:13:11,800 --> 00:13:13,760
The tongue just flaps against the roof of the mouth.

307
00:13:13,960 --> 00:13:14,440
No dot.

308
00:13:14,880 --> 00:13:15,480
But the Z.

309
00:13:15,920 --> 00:13:16,260
Z.

310
00:13:16,380 --> 00:13:18,040
I can feel my throat buzzing.

311
00:13:18,140 --> 00:13:19,520
That's your vocal cords vibrating.

312
00:13:19,700 --> 00:13:20,520
That's called voicing.

313
00:13:20,960 --> 00:13:24,020
You have to sustain the air pressure and engage the larynx.

314
00:13:24,120 --> 00:13:26,640
It costs more energy to say zizz than ra.

315
00:13:27,380 --> 00:13:28,360
So what happens?

316
00:13:28,460 --> 00:13:29,540
The Z gets a dot.

317
00:13:29,620 --> 00:13:31,180
Extra ink equals extra sound.

318
00:13:31,260 --> 00:13:32,100
It's so consistent.

319
00:13:32,100 --> 00:13:36,560
And the ultimate example is the S versus the shish, the sin and the shin.

320
00:13:36,640 --> 00:13:38,400
Oh, the shin has the most dots, right?

321
00:13:38,640 --> 00:13:40,480
It has three dots, the maximum payload.

322
00:13:40,660 --> 00:13:41,840
So let's trace the physics.

323
00:13:42,240 --> 00:13:44,100
The S sound sin is a hiss.

324
00:13:44,800 --> 00:13:45,760
It's a strident.

325
00:13:46,460 --> 00:13:48,720
It's a sharp, clear stream of air.

326
00:13:49,120 --> 00:13:51,340
The letter shape looks like three little teeth.

327
00:13:51,640 --> 00:13:52,220
No dots.

328
00:13:52,280 --> 00:13:53,280
It's the standard hiss.

329
00:13:53,480 --> 00:13:56,180
And the sh-shin, like in shu or shout.

330
00:13:56,420 --> 00:13:56,680
Shh.

331
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:57,300
Do it.

332
00:13:57,380 --> 00:13:57,860
Feel your mouth.

333
00:13:58,080 --> 00:13:59,060
You have to pull your tongue back.

334
00:13:59,060 --> 00:14:03,560
You have to dome the middle of your tongue up towards the hard palate that's called postal violer.

335
00:14:03,840 --> 00:14:06,360
And you had to blow a huge volume of turbulent air.

336
00:14:06,460 --> 00:14:09,040
It is a chaotic, high-energy sound.

337
00:14:09,140 --> 00:14:10,300
It washes over everything.

338
00:14:10,660 --> 00:14:13,180
And the script responds by dumping three dots on it.

339
00:14:13,340 --> 00:14:14,460
It's like a warning label.

340
00:14:14,940 --> 00:14:15,340
Caution.

341
00:14:16,220 --> 00:14:17,580
Heavy turbulence ahead.

342
00:14:18,460 --> 00:14:21,920
It's the most complex sound in that group, so it gets the most complex marking.

343
00:14:22,220 --> 00:14:23,640
Do you think the scribes knew this?

344
00:14:23,640 --> 00:14:28,700
Do they sit down and say, well, the postal violer fricative is complex, so let's add three dots?

345
00:14:29,060 --> 00:14:30,200
Almost certainly not.

346
00:14:30,260 --> 00:14:31,500
They didn't have MRI machines.

347
00:14:31,720 --> 00:14:34,120
They didn't have the vocabulary of modern linguistics.

348
00:14:34,380 --> 00:14:35,760
But they had their bodies.

349
00:14:35,920 --> 00:14:36,740
They felt the difference.

350
00:14:36,900 --> 00:14:38,920
They felt that she was heavier than S.

351
00:14:39,020 --> 00:14:41,120
They felt that Z was buzzier than R.

352
00:14:41,580 --> 00:14:45,660
And that somatic bodily intuition guided the evolution of the script.

353
00:14:46,220 --> 00:14:49,540
They added weight to the letter because they felt weight in the mouth.

354
00:14:49,540 --> 00:14:52,040
It really drives home the main point of the deep dive.

355
00:14:52,620 --> 00:14:54,480
The script is a recording of the body.

356
00:14:54,640 --> 00:14:56,000
It's not arbitrary squiggles.

357
00:14:56,240 --> 00:14:57,300
It's anatomical.

358
00:14:57,300 --> 00:14:59,580
It is the body leaving a trail in the sand.

359
00:15:00,080 --> 00:15:03,060
Speaking of anatomy, this leads us perfectly into segment two.

360
00:15:03,520 --> 00:15:07,420
Because if markedness is about the throat and the vocal cords, this next part is about

361
00:15:07,420 --> 00:15:08,200
the tongue itself.

362
00:15:08,740 --> 00:15:10,720
We need to talk about the sun and moon letters.

363
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:11,660
Ah, yes.

364
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:15,120
The bane of every Arabic student's existence.

365
00:15:15,520 --> 00:15:16,400
I remember trying to learn this.

366
00:15:16,740 --> 00:15:18,020
The teacher just hands you a list.

367
00:15:18,680 --> 00:15:19,580
Here are 14 letters.

368
00:15:20,400 --> 00:15:22,640
If the word starts with these, you pronounce the L.

369
00:15:23,220 --> 00:15:24,740
If it starts with those, you don't.

370
00:15:24,900 --> 00:15:25,360
Good luck.

371
00:15:25,500 --> 00:15:26,220
Memorize it.

372
00:15:26,220 --> 00:15:27,060
Don't ask why.

373
00:15:27,280 --> 00:15:27,440
Right.

374
00:15:27,540 --> 00:15:31,920
So for the listeners who don't know, in Arabic, the word for the is al.

375
00:15:32,540 --> 00:15:35,280
Like Al Jazeera or Al Qaeda or Al Qaeda.

376
00:15:35,960 --> 00:15:37,360
You hear the L. Clearly.

377
00:15:37,720 --> 00:15:37,980
Al.

378
00:15:38,040 --> 00:15:38,880
Those are the moon letters.

379
00:15:39,140 --> 00:15:40,280
The L stays strong.

380
00:15:40,380 --> 00:15:40,900
It behaves.

381
00:15:41,300 --> 00:15:42,860
But then you have words like the sun.

382
00:15:43,400 --> 00:15:44,940
In Arabic, sun is shams.

383
00:15:45,100 --> 00:15:45,960
You don't say al shams.

384
00:15:46,040 --> 00:15:47,040
You say ash shams.

385
00:15:47,180 --> 00:15:48,160
The L disappears.

386
00:15:48,380 --> 00:15:48,820
It melts.

387
00:15:49,040 --> 00:15:50,040
And the she gets doubled.

388
00:15:50,260 --> 00:15:50,920
Or the people.

389
00:15:51,840 --> 00:15:52,200
Anas.

390
00:15:52,800 --> 00:15:53,600
Not Elnas.

391
00:15:53,600 --> 00:15:54,860
The L becomes an N.

392
00:15:55,100 --> 00:15:55,280
Why?

393
00:15:55,480 --> 00:15:59,960
Why does the L surrender to the S or the N or the T, but it stands its ground against

394
00:15:59,960 --> 00:16:00,760
the K or the B?

395
00:16:01,340 --> 00:16:05,240
If you ask a traditional grammarian, they might give you a poetic answer about the sun burning

396
00:16:05,240 --> 00:16:05,900
up the stars.

397
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:08,200
But Flyxion says, look at the mouth.

398
00:16:08,320 --> 00:16:08,980
It's not poetry.

399
00:16:09,160 --> 00:16:09,600
It's biomechanics.

400
00:16:10,220 --> 00:16:11,100
It's the tongue map.

401
00:16:11,320 --> 00:16:11,640
Exactly.

402
00:16:11,820 --> 00:16:12,420
Let's do the anatomy.

403
00:16:12,580 --> 00:16:13,520
Where is the sound L made?

404
00:16:13,900 --> 00:16:14,500
Say so.

405
00:16:14,800 --> 00:16:18,340
My tongue is touching the roof of my mouth right behind my front teeth.

406
00:16:18,640 --> 00:16:18,960
Correct.

407
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:21,820
That is the coronal region, the crown of the tongue.

408
00:16:21,900 --> 00:16:24,300
Now, let's look at the sun letters, the ones that make the L melt.

409
00:16:24,780 --> 00:16:28,800
T, D, S, Z, N, R, S, H. Go through them.

410
00:16:29,140 --> 00:16:29,780
Where is your tongue?

411
00:16:30,260 --> 00:16:31,540
T, right behind the teeth.

412
00:16:32,580 --> 00:16:33,440
D, same spot.

413
00:16:33,700 --> 00:16:34,400
S, same spot.

414
00:16:34,760 --> 00:16:35,700
N, same spot.

415
00:16:35,940 --> 00:16:37,340
They are all coronal sounds.

416
00:16:37,500 --> 00:16:38,140
They are all neighbors.

417
00:16:38,360 --> 00:16:41,360
They all live in the same tiny apartment complex right behind your teeth.

418
00:16:41,560 --> 00:16:43,540
So what's happening when I try to say L shams?

419
00:16:43,800 --> 00:16:44,840
Think about the gymnastics.

420
00:16:44,840 --> 00:16:50,160
Your tongue goes up to the teeth for L, then it has to pull back a millimeter for shh.

421
00:16:50,620 --> 00:16:51,760
It's a stutter step.

422
00:16:52,240 --> 00:16:54,580
It's a rapid fire double tap in the same zone.

423
00:16:54,680 --> 00:16:55,240
It's inefficient.

424
00:16:55,780 --> 00:16:56,700
The tongue is lazy.

425
00:16:56,880 --> 00:16:58,420
It says, look, I'm already right here.

426
00:16:58,480 --> 00:17:01,020
Why don't I just skip the L and lean harder into the shit?

427
00:17:01,160 --> 00:17:01,740
It's a shortcut.

428
00:17:02,300 --> 00:17:03,300
It is assimilation.

429
00:17:03,620 --> 00:17:08,200
The tongue merges the two movements into one fluid gesture, ashams.

430
00:17:08,440 --> 00:17:09,020
It flows.

431
00:17:09,200 --> 00:17:09,980
It saves energy.

432
00:17:10,140 --> 00:17:12,220
With a moon letter like K or B.

433
00:17:12,340 --> 00:17:13,480
Say K, Alkitab.

434
00:17:13,480 --> 00:17:15,920
K is made way back in the throat, the vellum.

435
00:17:16,200 --> 00:17:17,300
It is far away from the L.

436
00:17:17,660 --> 00:17:18,940
So the tongue has to move anyway.

437
00:17:19,420 --> 00:17:19,820
Exactly.

438
00:17:20,040 --> 00:17:23,060
You have to travel from the teeth, L, to the throat, K.

439
00:17:23,220 --> 00:17:24,440
There is no shortcut available.

440
00:17:25,020 --> 00:17:28,840
Since you have to make the trip across the mouth anyway, you might as well pronounce the L.

441
00:17:29,120 --> 00:17:30,320
Oh, that makes so much sense.

442
00:17:30,420 --> 00:17:33,840
So the moon letters are just sounds that are geographically distant from the L.

443
00:17:34,500 --> 00:17:36,720
And sun letters are the neighbors.

444
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:38,160
It's not a grammar rule.

445
00:17:38,260 --> 00:17:40,380
It's a tongue cramp prevention strategy.

446
00:17:40,380 --> 00:17:43,940
It's your mouth naturally optimizing the path of motion.

447
00:17:44,100 --> 00:17:44,700
I love that.

448
00:17:44,880 --> 00:17:48,380
And the source points out a visual coincidence here that I find really funny.

449
00:17:48,840 --> 00:17:49,560
It's a heuristic.

450
00:17:49,840 --> 00:17:50,160
Yes.

451
00:17:50,480 --> 00:17:51,440
The toothy theory.

452
00:17:51,900 --> 00:17:56,600
Many of these sun letters, these tip of the tongue sounds, actually look like teeth in the script.

453
00:17:56,900 --> 00:17:57,800
Ideally, yes.

454
00:17:58,120 --> 00:17:59,320
The sin has three teeth.

455
00:17:59,800 --> 00:18:01,400
The sad has a loop and a tooth.

456
00:18:01,700 --> 00:18:02,800
The shin has teeth.

457
00:18:02,800 --> 00:18:08,040
Even the ta and ta are basically wide, shallow dishes with dots that look like eyes or teeth.

458
00:18:08,360 --> 00:18:10,440
Now, the paper is careful to say this wasn't designed.

459
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,600
The scribes didn't say, let's draw teeth because it's a tooth sound.

460
00:18:14,940 --> 00:18:16,340
No, that would be teleological.

461
00:18:16,860 --> 00:18:17,960
It would imply a plan.

462
00:18:18,340 --> 00:18:20,700
But it is a happy accident of evolution.

463
00:18:21,620 --> 00:18:25,680
Visually, the script inadvertently grouped these sounds into similar looking shapes.

464
00:18:25,880 --> 00:18:27,720
It matches the coronal clustering.

465
00:18:27,720 --> 00:18:33,880
It reminds me of the IPA chart, the International Phonetic Alphabet, where they map vowels based on where your tongue is.

466
00:18:33,960 --> 00:18:34,320
Exactly.

467
00:18:34,760 --> 00:18:37,600
Modern linguistics maps sounds by tongue position.

468
00:18:38,140 --> 00:18:44,340
Arabic orthography, the way it's written, intuitively group these consonants by articulatory proximity.

469
00:18:44,780 --> 00:18:46,700
It's like the script knows your mouth better than you do.

470
00:18:47,040 --> 00:18:49,400
I will never look at a sun letter the same way again.

471
00:18:49,600 --> 00:18:50,780
It's just my tongue being lazy.

472
00:18:50,960 --> 00:18:51,300
Efficient.

473
00:18:51,580 --> 00:18:51,880
Efficient.

474
00:18:52,100 --> 00:18:52,280
Okay.

475
00:18:52,640 --> 00:18:53,780
Moving on to segment three.

476
00:18:54,300 --> 00:18:56,660
We've talked about the skeleton, the dots, and the tongue.

477
00:18:56,660 --> 00:19:01,700
Now let's talk about the movement, the flow, the physics of cursive.

478
00:19:02,260 --> 00:19:04,080
This brings us back to that energy equation.

479
00:19:04,520 --> 00:19:06,100
Why do we write cursively at all?

480
00:19:06,220 --> 00:19:06,960
Why join letters?

481
00:19:07,160 --> 00:19:09,100
We take it for granted, but we don't have to.

482
00:19:09,320 --> 00:19:11,820
We could write like a typewriter, one letter at a time.

483
00:19:11,960 --> 00:19:12,280
Speed.

484
00:19:12,480 --> 00:19:13,440
Speed is the result.

485
00:19:13,680 --> 00:19:16,280
But the mechanism is reducing pen lifts.

486
00:19:16,400 --> 00:19:16,800
Pen lifts.

487
00:19:16,920 --> 00:19:17,820
Think about it physically.

488
00:19:18,240 --> 00:19:21,900
Every time you lift the pen off the paper, you are decelerating to zero.

489
00:19:22,100 --> 00:19:23,020
You have to stop.

490
00:19:23,100 --> 00:19:23,820
You have to hover.

491
00:19:24,100 --> 00:19:25,820
You have to re-aim to the next spot.

492
00:19:25,820 --> 00:19:27,980
You have to accelerate again to touch the paper.

493
00:19:28,180 --> 00:19:30,240
That is a massive waste of momentum.

494
00:19:30,640 --> 00:19:33,340
It's like driving in stop-and-go traffic versus driving on the highway.

495
00:19:33,580 --> 00:19:33,980
Exactly.

496
00:19:34,440 --> 00:19:35,280
Cursive is the highway.

497
00:19:35,700 --> 00:19:36,680
You keep the pen down.

498
00:19:36,860 --> 00:19:37,880
You preserve momentum.

499
00:19:38,360 --> 00:19:39,820
The ink flows continuously.

500
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:44,820
Mathematically, more joins equals fewer lifts equals lower energy costs.

501
00:19:44,940 --> 00:19:50,560
So pure laziness, sorry, efficiency, would dictate that we join absolutely everything.

502
00:19:50,680 --> 00:19:51,820
We should never lift the pen.

503
00:19:52,140 --> 00:19:54,780
One continuous line from the start of the book to the end.

504
00:19:54,780 --> 00:19:56,840
That would be the thermodynamic ideal.

505
00:19:57,240 --> 00:19:58,020
But there's a trap.

506
00:19:58,380 --> 00:19:59,020
The overshoot.

507
00:19:59,240 --> 00:20:00,520
What happens if you join everything?

508
00:20:00,740 --> 00:20:02,880
The letters lose their structural integrity.

509
00:20:03,380 --> 00:20:08,220
If you connect every loop to every line at high speed, everything starts to look like

510
00:20:08,220 --> 00:20:08,780
a sine wave.

511
00:20:09,120 --> 00:20:09,620
Just a wiggle.

512
00:20:09,940 --> 00:20:12,860
We've all seen someone's handwriting that looks like a seismograph reading.

513
00:20:12,860 --> 00:20:14,560
My doctor's prescription pad.

514
00:20:14,660 --> 00:20:17,700
I have no idea if it says ibuprofen or amputation.

515
00:20:18,320 --> 00:20:18,760
Exactly.

516
00:20:19,380 --> 00:20:22,560
You have maximized flow, but you have destroyed clarity.

517
00:20:22,800 --> 00:20:25,600
You have minimized energy, but you've maximized confusion.

518
00:20:25,920 --> 00:20:27,460
So how does Arabic handle this?

519
00:20:27,700 --> 00:20:29,920
Because Arabic is extremely cursive.

520
00:20:30,320 --> 00:20:31,720
It flows more than English cursive.

521
00:20:32,260 --> 00:20:34,620
It is, but it has a built-in braking system.

522
00:20:34,860 --> 00:20:35,600
And this is genius.

523
00:20:36,220 --> 00:20:40,700
There are six specific letters in the Arabic alphabet that refuse to connect to the left.

524
00:20:40,900 --> 00:20:42,000
The non-connecting letters.

525
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,580
They connect to the right, so you can flow into them from the previous letter, but you

526
00:20:45,580 --> 00:20:46,560
cannot flow out of them.

527
00:20:46,940 --> 00:20:50,340
You hit the letter, and the script forces you to lift the pen.

528
00:20:50,800 --> 00:20:58,860
These are the letters A, ELIF, D, DAO, DHDAO, R, R, Z, Z, and W, Y.

529
00:20:59,120 --> 00:20:59,420
Correct.

530
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:01,360
Now, why these six?

531
00:21:01,540 --> 00:21:02,200
Is it random?

532
00:21:02,500 --> 00:21:04,140
The expert in the paper says no.

533
00:21:04,360 --> 00:21:06,400
They act as structural boundary markers.

534
00:21:06,700 --> 00:21:08,960
The source calls them controlled interruptions.

535
00:21:09,060 --> 00:21:11,020
I love that term, controlled interruptions.

536
00:21:11,020 --> 00:21:11,960
Look at the ALIF.

537
00:21:12,080 --> 00:21:13,180
It's a vertical line.

538
00:21:13,280 --> 00:21:14,520
Just a stick, up and down.

539
00:21:14,820 --> 00:21:18,080
If you let that stick connect to the left, and you're writing quickly, it would look

540
00:21:18,080 --> 00:21:21,900
exactly like the letter LAM, L, which is also a vertical line that connects.

541
00:21:22,220 --> 00:21:25,420
So if ALIF connected, you wouldn't know if you were reading an A or an L.

542
00:21:25,560 --> 00:21:25,820
Right.

543
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:30,340
And since A and L are two of the most common letters, that would be a disaster.

544
00:21:30,900 --> 00:21:35,280
By forcing a pen lift after the ALIF, the script creates a patch of white space.

545
00:21:35,280 --> 00:21:37,780
That white space signals to the I.

546
00:21:38,200 --> 00:21:40,200
This vertical line stands alone.

547
00:21:40,520 --> 00:21:41,240
This is an A.

548
00:21:41,240 --> 00:21:43,260
And what about the D, the DAL?

549
00:21:43,520 --> 00:21:44,200
Same issue.

550
00:21:44,460 --> 00:21:46,380
The DAL is a small curved shape.

551
00:21:46,800 --> 00:21:50,220
If it connected to the left, it would look like a little tooth in the middle of a word,

552
00:21:50,320 --> 00:21:52,340
exactly like a B, T, N, or Y.

553
00:21:52,340 --> 00:21:54,060
It would disappear into the wave.

554
00:21:54,720 --> 00:21:58,180
By forcing a break, the script preserves the silhouette of the D.

555
00:21:58,560 --> 00:22:00,120
It says, this curve is important.

556
00:22:00,440 --> 00:22:01,120
Stop here.

557
00:22:01,420 --> 00:22:06,320
So these non-connecting letters are basically the script saying, whoa, slow down, lift the

558
00:22:06,320 --> 00:22:07,500
pen, reset the I.

559
00:22:07,620 --> 00:22:08,820
It's a negotiated peace treaty.

560
00:22:09,200 --> 00:22:10,340
The hand wants to keep moving.

561
00:22:10,440 --> 00:22:11,520
It wants to connect everything.

562
00:22:11,740 --> 00:22:14,000
The I says, if you connect that, I can't read it.

563
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:19,380
So the compromise is, connect most things, but break the circuit at these six specific

564
00:22:19,380 --> 00:22:21,580
points to maintain structural integrity.

565
00:22:22,020 --> 00:22:26,640
It's fascinating to think of white space, the empty space between letters, as a functional

566
00:22:26,640 --> 00:22:27,560
part of the system.

567
00:22:28,060 --> 00:22:30,460
Usually we think of the ink as the information.

568
00:22:31,160 --> 00:22:33,440
But the lack of ink is also information.

569
00:22:34,140 --> 00:22:35,600
Silence is part of the music.

570
00:22:36,100 --> 00:22:37,460
White space is part of the code.

571
00:22:37,920 --> 00:22:42,160
The paper makes a really interesting comparison here between Arabic and Hebrew.

572
00:22:42,560 --> 00:22:43,940
Because they're cousins, right?

573
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:44,840
Very close cousins.

574
00:22:45,140 --> 00:22:48,560
They both come from the same Semitic ancestor, the Phoenician-Aramaic tradition.

575
00:22:48,860 --> 00:22:50,760
They share the same roots, the same logic.

576
00:22:51,300 --> 00:22:54,700
But they chose completely different strategies for this stability.

577
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:55,280
Also.

578
00:22:55,660 --> 00:22:58,080
Hebrew chose the strategy of discreteness.

579
00:22:58,420 --> 00:23:03,080
If you look at the Hebrew script, the square script used in Torah scrolls, the letters are

580
00:23:03,080 --> 00:23:03,780
separate blocks.

581
00:23:03,960 --> 00:23:05,080
They generally don't touch.

582
00:23:05,080 --> 00:23:07,300
It looks very architectural, like bricks and a wall.

583
00:23:07,480 --> 00:23:08,020
It is.

584
00:23:08,320 --> 00:23:09,860
This maximizes clarity.

585
00:23:10,120 --> 00:23:13,940
It is very hard to confuse Hebrew letters because they are so distinct and separated.

586
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:16,060
But the cost is high energy.

587
00:23:16,180 --> 00:23:17,760
You are lifting the pen constantly.

588
00:23:18,080 --> 00:23:19,200
It's a high friction script.

589
00:23:19,560 --> 00:23:20,500
It is slow to write.

590
00:23:21,040 --> 00:23:22,020
And Arabic went the other way.

591
00:23:22,180 --> 00:23:23,520
Arabic chose continuity.

592
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:25,020
It maximized the flow.

593
00:23:25,160 --> 00:23:25,400
It said,

594
00:23:25,560 --> 00:23:30,300
We will accept the risk of ambiguity letters looking alike, and we will fix it with dots and

595
00:23:30,300 --> 00:23:34,340
context in exchange for the speed and low energy of cursive writing.

596
00:23:34,340 --> 00:23:36,580
That is a fascinating divergence.

597
00:23:37,140 --> 00:23:38,880
One went for stability through separation.

598
00:23:39,520 --> 00:23:41,220
The other for stability through flow.

599
00:23:41,480 --> 00:23:43,280
And you can even see it in the culture of the scripts.

600
00:23:43,880 --> 00:23:47,460
Hebrew feels monumental, timeless, static.

601
00:23:47,900 --> 00:23:49,580
It's carved in stone.

602
00:23:50,420 --> 00:23:52,640
Arabic feels kinetic, gestural.

603
00:23:52,840 --> 00:23:53,700
It's a fluid line.

604
00:23:53,800 --> 00:23:54,840
It's wind or water.

605
00:23:55,080 --> 00:23:57,860
It's like the difference between building a stone wall and flowing water.

606
00:23:58,120 --> 00:24:00,680
Both are strong, but in very different ways.

607
00:24:00,940 --> 00:24:01,700
Beautifully put.

608
00:24:01,840 --> 00:24:03,600
And that fluidity isn't just in the script.

609
00:24:03,740 --> 00:24:04,880
It's in the language itself.

610
00:24:05,100 --> 00:24:07,040
Which brings us to the engine under the hood.

611
00:24:07,180 --> 00:24:07,460
Yes.

612
00:24:07,700 --> 00:24:08,260
Segment four.

613
00:24:09,020 --> 00:24:09,460
Morphology.

614
00:24:09,740 --> 00:24:12,180
This is where we get into the generative aspect of the language.

615
00:24:12,300 --> 00:24:14,000
This might sound technical, but stay with us.

616
00:24:14,120 --> 00:24:15,940
Because it's like unlocking a secret code.

617
00:24:16,140 --> 00:24:19,040
This connects back to the minimal assembly concept.

618
00:24:19,340 --> 00:24:19,480
Yeah.

619
00:24:19,520 --> 00:24:22,060
How do you build a lot of meaning with very few parts?

620
00:24:22,160 --> 00:24:25,540
The source starts with a quick detour into numbers, which I thought was a great way to

621
00:24:25,540 --> 00:24:26,300
visualize this.

622
00:24:26,600 --> 00:24:26,960
Yes.

623
00:24:27,220 --> 00:24:28,920
Numerals as motor programs.

624
00:24:29,620 --> 00:24:30,480
Look at the number one.

625
00:24:30,580 --> 00:24:31,120
One stroke.

626
00:24:31,200 --> 00:24:32,360
Look at the Roman numeral, or three.

627
00:24:32,580 --> 00:24:33,140
Two strokes.

628
00:24:33,260 --> 00:24:33,720
Three strokes.

629
00:24:33,840 --> 00:24:34,580
It's tally logic.

630
00:24:34,880 --> 00:24:36,120
One mark for one thing.

631
00:24:36,220 --> 00:24:36,660
Exactly.

632
00:24:36,820 --> 00:24:37,280
It's additive.

633
00:24:38,100 --> 00:24:41,020
But try drawing nine lines every time you want to write the number nine.

634
00:24:41,140 --> 00:24:41,760
It's exhausting.

635
00:24:42,900 --> 00:24:43,640
The eye gets lost.

636
00:24:43,740 --> 00:24:44,520
You have to recount them.

637
00:24:44,740 --> 00:24:45,660
High energy cost.

638
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:47,100
High error rate.

639
00:24:47,900 --> 00:24:50,620
So as the numbers get higher, the symbols become abstract.

640
00:24:51,020 --> 00:24:53,460
The shape of nine doesn't look like nine things.

641
00:24:53,600 --> 00:24:55,020
It's just a symbol we agreed on.

642
00:24:55,020 --> 00:24:58,240
Because drawing nine lines is too expensive energetically.

643
00:24:58,520 --> 00:24:58,640
Right.

644
00:24:58,940 --> 00:25:03,480
So the system uses tally logic for the low numbers, where it's cheap and switches to

645
00:25:03,480 --> 00:25:05,880
abstract symbolic logic for the high numbers.

646
00:25:06,240 --> 00:25:06,700
It's efficient.

647
00:25:06,960 --> 00:25:10,420
And the paper argues that the Arabic language itself works the same way.

648
00:25:11,080 --> 00:25:12,440
The root and pattern system.

649
00:25:12,640 --> 00:25:14,640
This is the crown jewel of Semitic languages.

650
00:25:15,100 --> 00:25:16,460
And it's very different from English.

651
00:25:16,820 --> 00:25:22,100
In English, if I want to say write, writer, book, and office, those words sound totally different.

652
00:25:22,160 --> 00:25:23,900
You just have to memorize them as separate items.

653
00:25:23,900 --> 00:25:24,300
Right.

654
00:25:24,420 --> 00:25:28,260
There's no logical sound connection between write and office.

655
00:25:28,900 --> 00:25:30,200
They're just random labels.

656
00:25:30,720 --> 00:25:32,860
In Arabic, there is a deep logical connection.

657
00:25:33,140 --> 00:25:35,220
You have a root, a semantic skeleton.

658
00:25:36,320 --> 00:25:39,460
For anything related to writing, that root is K-T-B.

659
00:25:40,580 --> 00:25:42,460
Kaf, ta, ba.

660
00:25:43,260 --> 00:25:45,820
Those three consonants hold the idea of writing.

661
00:25:46,160 --> 00:25:47,440
So K-T-B isn't a word.

662
00:25:47,520 --> 00:25:48,140
It's a concept.

663
00:25:48,380 --> 00:25:49,080
It's the DNA.

664
00:25:49,320 --> 00:25:50,280
It's the raw material.

665
00:25:50,280 --> 00:25:55,120
Now, to make a word, you drop that root into a pattern or a template.

666
00:25:55,480 --> 00:25:58,580
Think of it like an algebraic formula or a function in code.

667
00:25:58,660 --> 00:25:59,280
Give us an example.

668
00:25:59,440 --> 00:26:00,300
Walk us through the algebra.

669
00:26:00,520 --> 00:26:00,680
Okay.

670
00:26:00,900 --> 00:26:03,020
There is a pattern for someone who does the action.

671
00:26:03,380 --> 00:26:04,820
That pattern is fa-el.

672
00:26:05,320 --> 00:26:08,340
You insert K-T-B into that pattern and you get kai-tib writer.

673
00:26:08,620 --> 00:26:08,860
Okay.

674
00:26:09,100 --> 00:26:09,460
K-T-B.

675
00:26:09,500 --> 00:26:11,840
There is a pattern for place where the action happens.

676
00:26:11,980 --> 00:26:13,280
That pattern is mat-f-el.

677
00:26:13,360 --> 00:26:13,480
True.

678
00:26:13,480 --> 00:26:17,220
You drop in K-T-B and you get mat-k-a-tib office or desk.

679
00:26:17,320 --> 00:26:17,700
The cup.

680
00:26:18,220 --> 00:26:19,020
The place of writing.

681
00:26:19,180 --> 00:26:19,520
Exactly.

682
00:26:19,860 --> 00:26:20,980
There is a pattern for instrument.

683
00:26:21,180 --> 00:26:22,160
A pattern for passive.

684
00:26:22,640 --> 00:26:26,180
If I want to say it was written, the pattern is fula-kutiba.

685
00:26:26,460 --> 00:26:29,360
And if I want to make it reciprocal, like writing to each other.

686
00:26:29,540 --> 00:26:30,680
There is a pattern for that too.

687
00:26:30,820 --> 00:26:31,340
Form three.

688
00:26:31,580 --> 00:26:31,980
Kataba.

689
00:26:32,420 --> 00:26:32,860
To correspond.

690
00:26:33,220 --> 00:26:33,960
To write back and forth.

691
00:26:34,040 --> 00:26:34,860
It's like a code.

692
00:26:34,980 --> 00:26:35,980
It's incredibly logical.

693
00:26:36,400 --> 00:26:37,860
It is a generative engine.

694
00:26:37,860 --> 00:26:41,460
You don't have to memorize a dictionary of random sounds.

695
00:26:41,460 --> 00:26:45,540
You memorize the roots, the meanings, and the patterns, the functions.

696
00:26:46,080 --> 00:26:49,200
Once you have the code, you can build words you've never even heard before.

697
00:26:49,940 --> 00:26:55,880
If you know the root for drink, S-H-R-B, and you know the pattern for place, make F-A-L,

698
00:26:56,120 --> 00:26:59,360
you can guess that mashrob means a place to drink.

699
00:26:59,600 --> 00:27:02,060
And the paper connects us back to the writing script.

700
00:27:02,200 --> 00:27:02,480
Yes.

701
00:27:02,780 --> 00:27:06,400
Just as the script uses a base shape plus dot to make a letter,

702
00:27:06,720 --> 00:27:09,600
the language uses root plus pattern to make a word.

703
00:27:09,600 --> 00:27:12,620
It's the same minimal assembly philosophy.

704
00:27:13,220 --> 00:27:18,940
You take a stable substrate, the skeleton, and you modify it slightly to create massive amounts of new meaning.

705
00:27:19,080 --> 00:27:20,040
It's incredibly elegant.

706
00:27:20,160 --> 00:27:22,580
It's like the language and the script are running on the same operating system.

707
00:27:22,660 --> 00:27:23,040
They are.

708
00:27:23,160 --> 00:27:28,800
And there's one specific mark the author mentions that perfectly encapsulates this time-stretching generative power.

709
00:27:29,280 --> 00:27:29,720
The Shada.

710
00:27:29,860 --> 00:27:31,040
The little W mark.

711
00:27:31,380 --> 00:27:31,740
Yes.

712
00:27:31,920 --> 00:27:33,920
The little W that sits on top of a letter.

713
00:27:34,500 --> 00:27:38,240
We talked about laziness earlier, but sometimes you need to emphasize something.

714
00:27:38,240 --> 00:27:41,480
The Shada indicates gemination, or doubling.

715
00:27:42,120 --> 00:27:46,560
If you see a Shada on a K, it's not a K. It's a KK. You hold the sound.

716
00:27:46,720 --> 00:27:49,300
Like in the word bookkeeper in English, that double K.

717
00:27:49,500 --> 00:27:49,940
Exactly.

718
00:27:50,320 --> 00:27:52,720
But in English, we usually rush through it.

719
00:27:53,160 --> 00:27:54,760
In Arabic, you must hold it.

720
00:27:54,840 --> 00:27:56,120
It creates a rhythmic stop.

721
00:27:56,560 --> 00:28:00,440
But here is the magic that doubling changes the meaning entirely.

722
00:28:00,800 --> 00:28:01,560
Give me an example.

723
00:28:01,560 --> 00:28:03,580
Take the root D-R-S.

724
00:28:04,360 --> 00:28:05,740
D-R-S means he studied.

725
00:28:06,060 --> 00:28:07,260
Just a simple past tense.

726
00:28:07,440 --> 00:28:07,920
D-R-S.

727
00:28:08,200 --> 00:28:08,860
He studied.

728
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:10,860
Now put a Shada on the middle letter.

729
00:28:11,200 --> 00:28:11,660
D-R-S.

730
00:28:11,780 --> 00:28:12,520
You double the R.

731
00:28:12,660 --> 00:28:13,000
D-R-S.

732
00:28:13,060 --> 00:28:13,980
That means he taught.

733
00:28:14,180 --> 00:28:14,660
Wait, really?

734
00:28:14,940 --> 00:28:16,820
He learned versus he taught.

735
00:28:16,920 --> 00:28:17,820
Those are opposites.

736
00:28:18,020 --> 00:28:20,100
And the only difference is holding the consonant longer.

737
00:28:20,340 --> 00:28:20,740
Yes.

738
00:28:21,240 --> 00:28:24,120
He studied implies he did the action to himself.

739
00:28:24,640 --> 00:28:26,520
He taught implies he made someone else study.

740
00:28:26,940 --> 00:28:30,900
That concept causative is triggered just by doubling the middle root letter.

741
00:28:30,900 --> 00:28:33,120
So physically, what does the Shada represent?

742
00:28:33,660 --> 00:28:35,740
It represents extending the sound in time.

743
00:28:36,400 --> 00:28:37,160
You hold the closure.

744
00:28:37,820 --> 00:28:44,300
It's a tiny, mark-minimal ink that indicates a major structural change in the timing of the word.

745
00:28:44,880 --> 00:28:47,680
A minimal mark for a major manipulation of time.

746
00:28:48,020 --> 00:28:48,960
That is poetic.

747
00:28:49,900 --> 00:28:55,840
A tiny, squiggly W that stretches time and reverses the flow of action from learning to teaching.

748
00:28:56,080 --> 00:28:57,740
That's the beauty of this system.

749
00:28:57,740 --> 00:29:00,880
It packs so much information into such small gestures.

750
00:29:01,180 --> 00:29:02,520
We're heading into segment five now.

751
00:29:02,740 --> 00:29:03,680
And I want to zoom out a bit.

752
00:29:04,060 --> 00:29:07,500
We've been very technical physics, anatomy, morphology.

753
00:29:07,700 --> 00:29:09,460
But writing is also cultural.

754
00:29:09,640 --> 00:29:10,200
It's historical.

755
00:29:10,380 --> 00:29:11,780
It carries the ghosts of the past.

756
00:29:11,880 --> 00:29:12,260
It does.

757
00:29:12,340 --> 00:29:13,100
It carries memory.

758
00:29:13,240 --> 00:29:16,560
Every time you write, you are reenacting thousands of years of history.

759
00:29:16,860 --> 00:29:19,080
The source talks about the ancestry of the alphabet.

760
00:29:19,400 --> 00:29:20,460
Where does this all come from?

761
00:29:20,620 --> 00:29:23,320
It traces back to the Phoenician and Proto-Sinaitic scripts.

762
00:29:23,440 --> 00:29:24,560
This was the compression event.

763
00:29:24,600 --> 00:29:26,020
Before this, we had hieroglyphs.

764
00:29:26,660 --> 00:29:27,720
Hieroglyphs in Egypt.

765
00:29:28,220 --> 00:29:29,680
Cuneiform and Mesopotamia.

766
00:29:29,880 --> 00:29:31,480
These are magnificent systems.

767
00:29:31,780 --> 00:29:33,640
But they were incredibly complex.

768
00:29:33,840 --> 00:29:35,100
You had thousands of symbols.

769
00:29:35,520 --> 00:29:36,580
Some stood for sounds.

770
00:29:36,740 --> 00:29:37,620
Some for whole words.

771
00:29:37,740 --> 00:29:38,460
Some for concepts.

772
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:41,200
You had to be an elite scribe to learn them.

773
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:43,120
You had to devote your life to it.

774
00:29:43,200 --> 00:29:44,680
It was proprietary technology.

775
00:29:44,880 --> 00:29:46,560
It kept the power in the hands of the few.

776
00:29:46,560 --> 00:29:47,160
Exactly.

777
00:29:47,880 --> 00:29:52,660
The invention of the alphabet around 1500 BC was a massive data compression.

778
00:29:53,680 --> 00:30:02,040
Some geniuses in the Sinai Peninsula, probably miners or workers, not elites, realized, wait, we don't need a picture for every word.

779
00:30:02,120 --> 00:30:04,120
We just need a symbol for every sound.

780
00:30:04,260 --> 00:30:07,400
So they compressed thousands of glyphs down to what?

781
00:30:07,620 --> 00:30:08,940
About 22 sounds.

782
00:30:09,140 --> 00:30:09,940
22 symbols.

783
00:30:10,140 --> 00:30:11,840
That is the ultimate minimal assembly.

784
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:12,920
It changed the world.

785
00:30:13,080 --> 00:30:14,420
It democratized literacy.

786
00:30:14,420 --> 00:30:16,480
You could teach a kid the alphabet in a week.

787
00:30:16,580 --> 00:30:17,860
You couldn't do that with hieroglyphs.

788
00:30:18,060 --> 00:30:19,920
It broke the monopoly on knowledge.

789
00:30:20,640 --> 00:30:21,660
But here's the cool part.

790
00:30:22,360 --> 00:30:27,840
Even though they stripped away the pictures, the ghosts of the pictures remained in the names of the letters.

791
00:30:28,060 --> 00:30:30,660
This is the midrashic memory the paper discusses.

792
00:30:31,120 --> 00:30:31,640
Midrashic.

793
00:30:32,060 --> 00:30:35,120
That refers to the tradition of interpreting biblical text, right?

794
00:30:35,380 --> 00:30:35,700
Yes.

795
00:30:36,280 --> 00:30:39,200
It's finding deep symbolic meanings in the details.

796
00:30:40,080 --> 00:30:43,420
Take the first letter, Aleph, or Elif in Arabic.

797
00:30:43,420 --> 00:30:45,260
It comes from the word for ox, right?

798
00:30:45,940 --> 00:30:47,540
Alp or Aleph meant ox.

799
00:30:48,160 --> 00:30:50,340
The original drawing was an ox head with horns.

800
00:30:50,980 --> 00:30:54,760
Over centuries, it rotated and simplified into the letter A we use today.

801
00:30:55,220 --> 00:30:57,020
Turn a capital A upside down.

802
00:30:57,360 --> 00:30:58,260
You see the horns.

803
00:30:58,460 --> 00:30:58,980
I see it.

804
00:30:59,040 --> 00:31:00,260
It's a triangle with legs.

805
00:31:00,480 --> 00:31:03,260
So the form became abstract, but the meaning stuck.

806
00:31:03,600 --> 00:31:06,820
The ox implies strength, leadership, the first one.

807
00:31:06,960 --> 00:31:09,200
And the second letter, bet or bat.

808
00:31:09,400 --> 00:31:10,500
Bet means house.

809
00:31:10,700 --> 00:31:12,200
So you have the ox and the house.

810
00:31:12,200 --> 00:31:15,380
And the paper mentions a narrative about the ox entering the house.

811
00:31:15,580 --> 00:31:15,680
Right.

812
00:31:16,040 --> 00:31:21,520
Midrashic interpretation might say, the strong leader, ox, enters the enclosure, house.

813
00:31:21,920 --> 00:31:23,020
It creates a story.

814
00:31:23,600 --> 00:31:25,820
Now, the expert insight here is crucial.

815
00:31:26,360 --> 00:31:30,540
The scribes probably didn't plan this narrative when they were simplifying the shapes.

816
00:31:30,640 --> 00:31:31,940
They were just trying to write faster.

817
00:31:32,060 --> 00:31:33,920
They weren't trying to write a philosophy book in the alphabet.

818
00:31:34,100 --> 00:31:35,360
So it wasn't a deliberate code.

819
00:31:35,720 --> 00:31:36,400
Likely not.

820
00:31:36,400 --> 00:31:41,660
But, and this is big, the fact that people interpreted it that way helped the alphabet survive.

821
00:31:41,820 --> 00:31:43,180
It's cultural stabilization.

822
00:31:43,560 --> 00:31:44,240
Ah, I see.

823
00:31:44,680 --> 00:31:48,320
If you believe the letter A is just a random line, you might change it.

824
00:31:48,620 --> 00:31:51,220
You might decide to draw it as a circle tomorrow because you're bored.

825
00:31:51,340 --> 00:31:51,700
Exactly.

826
00:31:51,920 --> 00:31:56,080
But if you believe A is the sacred ox of leadership, you don't touch it.

827
00:31:56,200 --> 00:31:56,920
You preserve it.

828
00:31:57,000 --> 00:31:57,860
It becomes sacred.

829
00:31:58,380 --> 00:32:01,080
This symbolic layering acts as a cultural glue.

830
00:32:01,080 --> 00:32:05,520
It kept the shape stable for thousands of years, even as languages changed.

831
00:32:05,880 --> 00:32:06,680
That's fascinating.

832
00:32:06,800 --> 00:32:09,420
So the physics, laziness, kept it efficient.

833
00:32:09,700 --> 00:32:12,980
But the stories, symbolism, kept it protected.

834
00:32:13,220 --> 00:32:13,660
Exactly.

835
00:32:13,860 --> 00:32:15,320
A dual layer of survival.

836
00:32:15,920 --> 00:32:19,580
The biological pressure to simplify and the cultural pressure to preserve.

837
00:32:19,980 --> 00:32:22,780
There is one last historical point in this segment about ligatures.

838
00:32:23,280 --> 00:32:27,620
We talked about how the script flows, but in the early days, it flowed a little too wildly.

839
00:32:28,140 --> 00:32:29,920
It was combinatorial explosion.

840
00:32:29,920 --> 00:32:34,500
In early manuscripts, the shape of a letter could change drastically depending on what

841
00:32:34,500 --> 00:32:36,580
letter came before it and what letter came after it.

842
00:32:36,780 --> 00:32:41,120
So an N might look one way next to a B and totally different next to an R.

843
00:32:41,360 --> 00:32:41,640
Right.

844
00:32:42,060 --> 00:32:46,680
And if you have 28 letters and each one changes based on its neighbors, you have thousands

845
00:32:46,680 --> 00:32:48,000
of possible combinations.

846
00:32:48,700 --> 00:32:50,860
That is a huge cognitive load for a writer.

847
00:32:51,040 --> 00:32:53,020
You have to remember too many shapes.

848
00:32:53,300 --> 00:32:54,140
So how did they fix it?

849
00:32:54,840 --> 00:32:55,320
Standardization.

850
00:32:55,320 --> 00:32:57,960
They boiled it down to just four positions.

851
00:32:58,700 --> 00:33:04,760
Initial, start of word, medial, middle, final, end, and isolated, alone.

852
00:33:04,980 --> 00:33:05,380
That's it.

853
00:33:05,600 --> 00:33:06,100
Just four.

854
00:33:06,320 --> 00:33:06,780
Just four.

855
00:33:07,100 --> 00:33:10,680
Instead of infinite variations, you only need to learn four shapes per letter.

856
00:33:11,160 --> 00:33:14,760
And honestly, for most letters, the initial and medial are basically the same.

857
00:33:15,180 --> 00:33:17,140
This was another massive optimization.

858
00:33:17,560 --> 00:33:19,500
It reduced the search space for the brain.

859
00:33:19,500 --> 00:33:23,180
It's like they were constantly patching the software to make it run smoother on the human

860
00:33:23,180 --> 00:33:23,560
hardware.

861
00:33:23,860 --> 00:33:24,940
That is the perfect metaphor.

862
00:33:25,100 --> 00:33:26,820
The hardware is our hand and eye.

863
00:33:27,080 --> 00:33:28,240
The software is the script.

864
00:33:28,620 --> 00:33:32,880
And for centuries, they were optimizing the code to run as efficiently as possible on that

865
00:33:32,880 --> 00:33:33,920
biological machine.

866
00:33:34,300 --> 00:33:38,840
So bringing this all together, we started with the mission to understand how laziness and

867
00:33:38,840 --> 00:33:40,220
clarity fought each other.

868
00:33:40,400 --> 00:33:44,100
And we found that the Arabic script is essentially a peace treaty between them.

869
00:33:44,380 --> 00:33:45,160
It is an equilibrium.

870
00:33:45,600 --> 00:33:46,880
Let's recap the balance points.

871
00:33:46,880 --> 00:33:52,020
It balances speed, cursive, against legibility, dots, and non-connecting letters.

872
00:33:52,300 --> 00:33:57,980
It balances the skeleton, the motor flow, against the augmentation, the specific information.

873
00:33:58,340 --> 00:34:02,700
It balances the root, the concept, against the pattern, the function.

874
00:34:02,960 --> 00:34:07,580
It really is a durable residue of embodied production, to quote the paper again.

875
00:34:08,020 --> 00:34:11,660
It looks the way it does because human hands are lazy and human eyes are picky.

876
00:34:11,800 --> 00:34:12,700
And because it worked.

877
00:34:13,060 --> 00:34:13,860
It survived.

878
00:34:13,860 --> 00:34:17,280
It transmitted knowledge across empires and centuries.

879
00:34:17,560 --> 00:34:20,020
It is an incredibly successful piece of technology.

880
00:34:20,680 --> 00:34:24,980
Now, before we go, the expert in the source poses a final provocative thought.

881
00:34:25,280 --> 00:34:28,200
And this is something I want our listeners to really mull over.

882
00:34:28,420 --> 00:34:28,800
Yes.

883
00:34:29,140 --> 00:34:31,800
We've spent this whole hour talking about embodied constraint.

884
00:34:32,080 --> 00:34:35,080
The ink flow, the friction of the pen, the cramp of the hand.

885
00:34:35,280 --> 00:34:35,460
But...

886
00:34:35,460 --> 00:34:36,480
We don't write like that anymore.

887
00:34:36,600 --> 00:34:37,060
We type.

888
00:34:37,220 --> 00:34:39,580
I am tapping on glass or clicking plastic keys.

889
00:34:39,740 --> 00:34:40,820
The friction is gone.

890
00:34:41,100 --> 00:34:42,000
The ink is gone.

891
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:44,380
The motor constraint of the curve is gone.

892
00:34:44,520 --> 00:34:45,100
Think about it.

893
00:34:45,340 --> 00:34:50,240
The energy cost of typing a Z is the exact same as typing an A. It's just a keystroke.

894
00:34:50,520 --> 00:34:55,240
The energy cost of typing a complex letter like shin is the same as a simple letter like ba.

895
00:34:55,400 --> 00:34:55,880
Whoa.

896
00:34:56,220 --> 00:35:00,640
So the economic pressure that shaped the script has evaporated.

897
00:35:00,740 --> 00:35:01,780
It has shifted entirely.

898
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:03,880
The thermodynamic landscape has changed.

899
00:35:03,880 --> 00:35:11,740
So the question is, if writing systems evolve like biological organisms under pressure, what happens now that the pressure is gone?

900
00:35:12,320 --> 00:35:12,980
Or changed?

901
00:35:13,360 --> 00:35:15,240
Will our scripts lose their efficiency?

902
00:35:15,620 --> 00:35:16,560
Will they become bloated?

903
00:35:16,780 --> 00:35:19,280
Or will we see new forms of dots and ligatures?

904
00:35:19,500 --> 00:35:20,400
Think about emojis.

905
00:35:20,780 --> 00:35:21,220
Emojis.

906
00:35:21,340 --> 00:35:22,280
Think about a text message.

907
00:35:22,560 --> 00:35:23,960
It's often ambiguous, right?

908
00:35:24,240 --> 00:35:25,700
Tone is hard to read in plain text.

909
00:35:26,040 --> 00:35:26,360
Fine.

910
00:35:26,420 --> 00:35:28,080
Does that mean I'm good or I'm angry?

911
00:35:28,320 --> 00:35:30,300
It's the RASM problem all over again.

912
00:35:30,440 --> 00:35:33,900
It's ambiguous, the letters are clear, but the intent is blurry.

913
00:35:34,180 --> 00:35:34,900
So what do we do?

914
00:35:35,100 --> 00:35:36,480
We add a smiley face.

915
00:35:37,120 --> 00:35:38,380
Or a thumbs up.

916
00:35:38,480 --> 00:35:39,420
Or a spell emoji.

917
00:35:39,600 --> 00:35:40,300
We add a dot.

918
00:35:40,540 --> 00:35:41,220
We add a dot.

919
00:35:41,840 --> 00:35:43,760
The emoji is the new diacritic.

920
00:35:44,320 --> 00:35:48,380
It is a minimal assembly added to the text to clarify the emotional intent.

921
00:35:48,760 --> 00:35:53,800
It's cheap energy-wise, just a click, but it has high informational return.

922
00:35:54,120 --> 00:35:55,080
That is a wild thought.

923
00:35:55,360 --> 00:35:56,820
Emojis are the new vowel marks.

924
00:35:56,820 --> 00:35:59,900
We might be watching a new stabilization happen in real time.

925
00:36:00,520 --> 00:36:04,760
The digital age is a new environment, and the organism of language is adapting again.

926
00:36:05,240 --> 00:36:08,860
It's finding a new equilibrium between speed and clarity.

927
00:36:09,320 --> 00:36:11,560
I'm going to be thinking about that every time I'm in the text message now.

928
00:36:12,220 --> 00:36:15,580
Every time I hesitate and add a lull, just to make sure I don't sound mean.

929
00:36:15,700 --> 00:36:19,160
That lull is you being an efficient scribe, preventing ambiguity.

930
00:36:19,660 --> 00:36:20,920
You are part of the evolution.

931
00:36:21,460 --> 00:36:24,120
Well, on that note, we are going to wrap up this deep dive.

932
00:36:24,120 --> 00:36:28,360
I hope you look at the next piece of writing you see, whether it's Arabic, English, or

933
00:36:28,360 --> 00:36:32,420
a text message, and see the invisible history of muscles and nerves behind it.

934
00:36:32,500 --> 00:36:34,800
It's all just human energy, preserved in ink and pixels.

935
00:36:35,140 --> 00:36:35,760
Thanks for listening.

936
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:37,200
We'll see you in the next deep dive.

